<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06171112 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06171112 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Associated Press; Dependents arrive Tuesday at McChord airbase  (color); PHOTO: Associated Press; Workers sweep Manila InternationalAirport's runway today; only a handful of flights are operating  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO; DISASTER; REFUGEE; MILITARY; FAMILY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The first wave of the 20,000 soldiers and family members fleeing thePhilippines' Mount Pinatubo volcano arrived in the continental United Statesovernight after a 2 1/2-day journey by air and sea.;    A chartered jumbo jetcarrying 357 evacuees, mostly spouses and children of soldiers at Clark AirBase, arrived from Hawaii late Tuesday. They went through customs and weregiven commercial airline tickets to their hometowns.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  VOLCANO REFUGEES HEADING FOR HOME20,000 FLEEING TO U.S. FROM PHILIPPINES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO><TEXT>     They are among 20,000 U.S. military personnel and dependents evacuated fromClark and from Subic Bay Naval Base in the Philippines after Mount Pinatubobegan a series of eruptions June 9 that have killed 169 people.;    Some ofthe early arrivals told harrowing stories of seeing collapsed buildings and acountryside covered in white volcanic ash. Some said they had to flee with nomore than the clothes on their backs.;    &quot;I've never been in an earthquake, avolcano and a typhoon at the same time before,&quot; said Air Force Capt. CliffBreier, who managed to get his Doberman dog on the evacuation plane.;    &quot;Youcould see the hills in the distance. It looked like the Alps. Everything wasash gray or white,&quot; said Air Force Capt. Scott Weyant.;    Air Force MasterSgt. Benjamin Reese said he and his family were moved twice at Subic becausethe weight of the ash was too much for base buildings.;    &quot;The fire station Iknow was totally collapsed on its trucks,&quot; he said.;    Air Force securitypoliceman Joseph Callahan said he and his colleagues worked 14-hour shifts tokeep looters away from Clark.;    As many as 5,000 of the soldiers and theirrelatives are expected to arrive at McChord in the next few days, said Sgt.Jim Davis, base spokesman.;    The first arrivals were offered medical care,travel expenses and money for clothing and other needs. Dozens of phones wereprovided so they could call home.;    &quot;Some people got out with literally noshoes, nothing, because buildings were collapsing on them,&quot; said HollyErickson, wife of an Air Force captain.;    Air Force Capt. John Litten saidpeople had to flee with only the few possessions they could carry aboard theplane. That included a dozen cats and dogs.;    &quot;Whatever they left behind,they can expect never to see again,&quot; he said.;    Their 2 1/2-day journeybegan aboard Navy ships that left Subic Bay for the Philippine island of Cebu.From there, they flew to Guam and then on to Hawaii before the final flight toMcChord, said Navy Lt. Ron Barkdull.;    One of the evacuees, Debbie Parker,of Roanoke, Va., said by phone from Guam earlier Tuesday that she and herthree children were waiting to hear when her husband, Maj. Greg Parker, wouldbe joining them.;    &quot;I've heard that my husband has evacuated and I don'tknow where he is,&quot; she said. &quot;I would love to know because that is the onlything that is bothering me right now besides wanting everyone out.&quot;;    Littensaid some of the evacuees who arrived at McChord would begin leaving forhometowns across the country as early as today.;    About 60 people inmilitary and civilian clothes were on hand to greet the first arrivals.;    InManila, meanwhile, foreign flights out of the capital's crippled airportresumed today as Mount Pinatubo's daily eruptions entered their second week.At least three more earth tremors were recorded and an explosion blanketedClark Air Base with more ash.;    Still, scientists said Pinatubo was steadilycalming and they reduced the danger zone from a radius of 18 to 12 miles. Thatstill encompasses Clark, which is 10 miles east of the volcano.;    Food andclean drinking water were running low in central and southwestern portions ofLuzon island, which includes the volcano and Manila. Thousands of homes wereburied in ash and hundreds of thousands of people are homeless.;    Manila'sNinoy Aquino International Airport remained officially closed today, butplanes from Quantas, Lufthansa, Cathay Pacific and Singapore airlines left &quot;attheir own risk&quot; with passengers aboard.;    They had been stranded bySaturday's huge eruption.;    Airport officials said planes from otherairlines were still stranded.;    No new ash has fallen since Saturday onManila, 60 miles south of the volcano, but the city's air remained cloggedwith fine, sand-like debris.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; Donations can be mailed tothe following organizations. Checks should be marked clearly for the volcanorelief effort.;    (check) Philippine Consulate General, 447 Sutter St., SanFrancisco, CA 94108, (415) 433-6666.;    (check) The Filipino American Chamberof Commerce Volcano Relief Fund, 72 N. Fifth St., San Jose, CA 95112, (408)283-0833.;    (check) The Filipino-American Council of Union City, 3325 SanPedro Court, Union City, CA 94587.;    (check) Ilocano National Association,c/o Emmanuel S. Tipon, 564 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94105, (415)929-3531.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Mcchord Air Force Base, Wash.  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910619  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  838  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday June 19, 199100171112,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRG